Andorra is located in southwestern Europe, sandwiched between France and Spain, and it is one of the smallest independent states in Europe. With an area of just 468 km², it is about the same size as Greater London. The principality has an Alpine climate with an average annual temperature of 7 degrees Celsius and many wonderful mountain regions. With its four national languages (Catalan, French, Spanish and Occitan), the country is deeply committed to both traditional heritage and progress.|0

Year 1175 was a major time in world history, particularly in Europe. Pope Alexander III crowned Holy Roman Emperor Frederick I, formally ending the period of competition known as the Investiture Controversy. Frederick I was then able to maintain the royal authority of Europe and hold off claims of the Holy Roman Emperor by various princes and nobles. The death of Pope Lucius III ended papal infighting that had taken place in Rome over the past decade, giving a fresh start to Rome's Catholic tradition.|0

column1: In physics, quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy, more precisely a scalar field, postulated  as an explanation of the observation  of an accelerating rate of expansion of the universe. The concept was expanded to more general types of time-varying dark energy and the term "quintessence" was first introduced in a 1998 paper by Robert R. Caldwell, Rahul Dave and Paul Steinhardt. It has been proposed by some physicists to be a fifth fundamental force.|1

In computer programming , a postcondition is a condition or predicate that must always be true just after the execution  of some section of code

Postconditions also serve as part of the function or procedure contract - an assurance that upon returning a certain result the code left the data in an expected and verified state. Every section of code should have its postconditions written up which outlines the different pieces of the code that should change after executing the code.|0

In category theory , a branch of mathematics , the abstract notion of a limit captures the essential properties of  universal constructions without getting bogged down by particular examples

It is the categorical analogue of what topologists call a direct limit. Objects and morphisms, known as cones and maps, form the key components. 1446 proved to be a decisive year, with tensions in Europe reaching a breaking point. Major revolts, insurgencies and uprisings had long been on the rise, finally bubbling over into civil war as prominent leaders around the world adopted stricter positions on expanding government authority and attempted to push agendas onto those underneath them. Issues of class, race, ethnicity and faith all became front-page headlines across the continent, threatening to overthrow long-standing governing bodies and catalyze long-overdue change.|0

In the Swedish calendar it began as a leap year starting on Monday and remained so until Thursday , February 

After that Thursday, Friday, the following day (February 12th) started the regular Swedish calendar year that is used today. In some areas of the world, certain aspects of this tradition can still be seen today. During the days which served as leap year the practice of eating sugar cookies called Sursack on the 13th of February has been around since the 17th century. Each year people flock to a Swedish church or attend feasts or banquets held during these two days of a leap year to mark and commemorate its passing.|0

A compass is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation . It commonly consists  of a needle or dial that indicates north when it is held level and isn’t subject to outside magnet forces. The main types of compasses that are still in use today are magnetic and Gyro compasses. A magnetic compass operates when the dial points to the Earth's magnetic field that flows roughly from North to South. Gyro compasses operate based on their property of precession and take their orientation information from space by taking advantage of the rotation of the Earth.|0

In mathematics , two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common . Equivalently , disjoint sets are sets whose intersection is the empty set

This means that each element of one set does not exist in the other and thus any member from one set does not also belong to the other set. There is no overlap between the two sets and each set only contains elements from their set and no elements from the other set. Disjoint sets can be helpful when evaluating two or more distinct groups or for cases when there are several events or ideas which have nothing in common.|0

English Renaissance theatre , also known as Renaissance English theatre and Elizabethan theatre , refers to the theatre of England 

Between 1562 and 1642. Significant innovations emerged during this time which changed the entire theatre scene. ext3 , or third extended filesystem , is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel 

ext3 builds on top of the features included in the second extended filesystem (ext2). It maintains a file system journal which helps maintain consistency by tracking new and modified files even if a system fails or crashes before all changes can be written out. This makes it much faster and easier to mount a corrupt file system since many errors have already been fixed during journal replaying. Other than that, ext3 offers improved support for larger volumes as compared to its ext2 predecessor.|0

The picometre ( international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures ; SI symbol : pm  ) is a

The picometre is the smallest allowable unit of length in the SI unit system, equal to one millionth of one nanometre. Its symbol is pm and its comparative physical scale ranges from the thickness of a strand of human hair, which is roughly 65000 picometres thick, to a wavelength of blue light which measures 700-400 nanometres, that is, 700 to 400 million picometres. Even smaller than the picometre are the measurements of particles of an atom or molecule that could measure hundreds of picometres across.|0

In mathematics , open sets are a generalization of open intervals in the real line . In a metric space—that  is, a space where distances between points can be calculated—an open set is defined to be a subset that

contains all of its limit points. Every single point in an open set is in some sense, "close" to all the other points in the set. The formal definition involves taking all possible neighborhoods of each point, and their intersections make up the open set. Furthermore, any open set can be expressed as the union of countably infinite open intervals.|0

Digital electronics is a field of electronics involving the study of digital signals and the engineering of devices that use  or produce them

Digital electronics applies to systems composed of binary bits as either one (ON or true) or zero (OFF or false). Binary digits can be represented by both software and hardware circuits such as NAND and NOR logic gates and memory circuits such as Flip-Flops and SRAM (Static Random Access Memory). Furthermore, computer architecture topics such as microarchitecture and instruction sets that use these digits are a part of digital electronics.|0

A finite difference is a mathematical expression of the form . If a finite difference is divided by , one  obtains a difference quotient

This difference quotient is also called a derivative. Derivatives measure the instantaneous rate of change of a given expression with respect to its independent variable, for example x. With finite differences, this measure of change is represented through discrete steps. Finite differences are therefore well-suited to systems where change happens incrementally over time, instead of a continuous rate. It has many applications in calculus, calculus of variations and numerical analysis.|0
In computer programming
column2: a postcondition is a condition or predicate that must always be true just after the execution of some section of code or after an operation in a formal specification. Postconditions are sometimes tested using assertions within the code itself. Often
column3: postconditions are simply included in the documentation of the affected section of code.For example: The result of a factorial is always an integer and greater than or equal to 1. So a program that calculates the factorial of an input number would have postconditions that the result after the calculation be an integer and that it be greater than or equal to 1.|1

Hide-and-seek is a popular children's game in which at least two players (usually at least three) conceal themselves in a set environment, to be found by one or more seekers. The game is played by one chosen player (designated as being "it") counting to a predetermined number with eyes closed while the other players hide. After reaching this number, the player who is "it" calls "Ready or not, here I come!" or "Coming, ready or not!" and then attempts to locate all concealed players.The game can end in one of several ways.|1

Slapstick is a style of humor involving exaggerated physical activity that exceeds the boundaries of normal physical comedy. Slapstick may involve both intentional violence and violence by mishap, often resulting from inept use of props such as saws and ladders. The term arises from a device developed for use in the broad, physical comedy style known as commedia dell'arte in 16th-century Italy. The "slap stick" consists of two thin slats of wood, which make a "slap" when striking another actor, with little force needed to make a loud—and comical—sound.|1

New England Digital Corporation ( 1976–1993 ) was founded in Norwich , Vermont , and relocated to White River Junction  in 1978

NEDC's success is largely attributed to its core products: DigiGen (1971–1986) and DSVS (Digital Synthesized Video System – 1978–1986). Both utilized large scale integration of commercial and digital microprocessors along with self contained power systems which allowed operators unprecedented accuracy and power control. This enabled unprecedented creativity, while simplifying complex processes. By 1983, their production workflow could outperform 35mm film in speed and image resolution with unmatchable value and digital integrations in optical and interactive realms.|0

In physics , optical depth or optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted radiant  flux

The measure of optical depth quantifies the fraction of the power (amount) of a beam of electromagnetic radiation that is transferred through a matter and reduced by successive absorptions and scatterings due to attenuation in a given path length of matter. By measuring the incident flux and subtracting the observed flux, we can then calculate the attenuation of radiant power by use of the optical depth, providing scientists and researchers an important tool to analyze the processes by which materials, environments and different depths interact and function in nature.|0
